Logistic Regression - Intro ......

So far, we used Regression to predict numbers (like exam scores or house prices).
But what if the question is Yes/No instead of a number?

Example Intuition
Imagine we want to predict if a student will Pass (1) or Fail (0) based on study hours.

## If we use Linear Regression, we might get predictions like:
2 hours → 0.3
3 hours → 0.7
5 hours → 1.2
But values like 1.2 or negative numbers don’t make sense as probabilities.

## Logistic Regression fixes this by turning those values into a probability between 0 and 1.
2 hours → 0.3 (30% chance of passing)
3 hours → 0.7 (70% chance of passing)
5 hours → 0.95 (95% chance of passing)

## Finally, we set a simple threshold (commonly 0.5):
If probability ≥ 0.5 → predict Pass (1)
If probability < 0.5 → predict Fail (0)

image
This way, Logistic Regression gives both a probability and a Yes/No decision.

Important Note Don’t get confused by the name!

Linear Regression → predicts numbers (continuous values).
Logistic Regression → predicts categories (usually Yes/No).
So even though it has "regression" in the name, it’s actually a classification algorithm.

